Diversity Outbred Micxe

Brian S. Yandell

12/16/2016

This is a study of Diversity Outbred (DO) mice derived from 8 founder strains.

Data: https://github.com/rqtl/qtl2data/
Reference: Recla JM, Robledo RF, Gatti DM, Bult CJ, Churchill GA, Chesler EJ (2014) Precise genetic mapping and integrative bioinformatics in Diversity Outbred mice reveals Hydin as a novel pain gene. Mamm Genome 25:211-222. doi:10.1007/s00335-014-9508-0 Here are some useful links:

  • http://rqtl.org (lots of useful stuff here)
    • A brief tour of R/qtl: [pdf | code]
    • A shorter tour of R/qtl: [pdf | code]
    • R/qtl sample data formats
    • A Guide to QTL Mapping with R/qtl by Karl W. Broman & aunak Sen
  • http://kbroman.org/qtl2/
    • See Installation Instructions
    • R/qtl User Guide
    • R/qtl2 input file format
    • R/qtl2ggplot: Yandell version of qtl2plot with grammar of graphics plots (ggplot2)

Files for DO mice are in the https://github.com/rqtl/qtl2data/tree/master/DOex. You will need DOex.zip and c2_snpinfo.rds. This is a small subset for teaching purposes of the larger dataset.

Setup

First we set up needed packages, or libraries.

library(qtl2geno)
library(qtl2scan)
library(qtl2ggplot)

Could read in data over the internet. We do it here with local copy, which is downloaded if not found.

do_file <- "DOex.zip"
snp_file <- "c2_snpinfo.rds"

Get files from internet if they do not exist locally.

web_address <- file.path("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rqtl/",
               "qtl2data/master/DOex")
if(!file.exists(do_file)) {
  download.file(file.path(web_address, do_file), do_file, quiet=TRUE)
}
if(!file.exists(snp_file)) {
  download.file(file.path(web_address, snp_file), snp_file, quiet=TRUE)
}
rm(web_address)

Read cross object and subset to chr 2.

DOex <- read_cross2(do_file)
summary(DOex)
## Object of class cross2 (crosstype "do")
## 
## No. genotyped lines          261
## No. phenotyped individuals   261
## 
## No. phenotypes                 1
## No. covariates                 6
## No. phenotype covariates       0
## 
## No. chromosomes                3
## Total markers                320
## No. markers by chr:
##   2   3   X 
## 125 102  93

Calculate genotype probabilities.

Calculate genotype probabilities. This can take some time and may create a huge file. We reduce to the 8 allele probabilities, which is smaller. We also put the physical map into the probs object. For larger datasets, we save both objects, as they took some time to create.

pr <- calc_genoprob(DOex, error_prob=0.002)

Convert to allele probabilities. Switch map to physical map in Mbp.

apr <- genoprob_to_alleleprob(pr)
apr$map <- DOex$pmap

QTL Scan on chr 2

pheno_scan <- scan1(apr, DOex$pheno)
plot(pheno_scan)

QTL scan with kinship adjustment.

Calculate kinship matrices using the "loco" option (calculate kinship for each chromosome using SNPs from all but that chromosome).

kinship <- calc_kinship(apr, "loco")

Create a copy of the phenotype matrix and rename the phenotype to "OF_kinship" for plotting purposes. Do genome scan.

pheno_2 <- DOex$pheno
dimnames(pheno_2)[[2]] <- "OF_kinship"
pheno_scan_2 <- scan1(apr, pheno_2, kinship)
plot(pheno_scan_2)

Bind the two scans together and plot.

pheno_scan_2 <- cbind(pheno_scan, pheno_scan_2)
plot(pheno_scan_2, 1:2)

Subset to chr 2

plot(pheno_scan_2, 1:2, chr="2")

Set up SNP info on chr 2.

Read snpinfo from file.

snpinfo <- readRDS(snp_file)

Calculate strain distribution patterns.

snpinfo$sdp <- calc_sdp(snpinfo[,-(1:4)])

Convert to snp probabilities.

snppr <- genoprob_to_snpprob(apr[,"2"], snpinfo)

SNP association analysis

Perform SNP association analysis.

out_snps <- scan1(snppr, DOex$pheno, kinship[["2"]])

Plot results

plot(out_snps, cex=2, drop.hilit=2.5)

Show strain distribution patterns in SNPs.

plot(out_snps, patterns="all",drop.hilit=2.5,cex=2)

Show only top strain distribution patterns in SNPs.

plot(out_snps, patterns="hilit",drop.hilit=2.5,cex=2, ylim=c(4,8))
